{
  "texts": [
    "Yet it is very unlikely that contextualized norms for these exact sentences would already exist, precisely because there are an infinite number of contexts in which a given word could occur-thus requiring researchers to collect their own norms.",
    "This means that even a very large dataset of contextualized judgments may have limited direct practical application.",
    "The current work investigates a potential solution to this problem: using large language models (LLMs) to augment psycholinguistic datasets.",
    "If LLMs provide judgments that are sufficiently humanlike, then a small dataset of human norms (i.e., a \"gold standard\") could be rapidly scaled to encompass more words, more semantic dimensions, and more contexts-all at substantially lower cost.",
    "If, however, LLMs prove unreliable-i.e., their responses diverge too much from those of humans-then it is important to quantify both the source and extent of this unreliability."
  ]
}